questions.solution:
**Compiler error occurs**: `class Foo inherits unrelated defaults for greet() from types A and B`.

**Resolution**: The implementing class must override `greet()` and explicitly decide which to call (or provide its own implementation):

```java
interface A { default void greet() { System.out.println("A"); } }
interface B { default void greet() { System.out.println("B"); } }

class Foo implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void greet() {
        A.super.greet(); // explicitly call A's default
        // or B.super.greet();
        // or provide your own implementation
    }
}
```

This is Java's solution to the 'diamond problem' — the compiler forces explicit resolution rather than guessing.

```java
// Interface: contract all payment methods must fulfil
interface Payable {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);
    double getTransactionFee(double amount);
}

// Abstract class: shared logic for card-based payments
abstract class CardPayment implements Payable {
    private String cardNumber;
    protected boolean validateCard() {
        return cardNumber != null && cardNumber.length() == 16;
    }
}

// Concrete card implementations
class CreditCard extends CardPayment {
    @Override public boolean processPayment(double amount) { /* ... */ return true; }
    @Override public double getTransactionFee(double amount) { return amount * 0.02; }
}

class DebitCard extends CardPayment {
    @Override public boolean processPayment(double amount) { /* ... */ return true; }
    @Override public double getTransactionFee(double amount) { return 0.50; }
}

// Non-card methods implement interface directly
class PayPal implements Payable {
    @Override public boolean processPayment(double amount) { /* OAuth flow */ return true; }
    @Override public double getTransactionFee(double amount) { return amount * 0.029 + 0.30; }
}
```

This separates the contract (interface) from shared implementation (abstract class).

