questions.question:
Review this supposedly immutable class:
```java
public final class Config {
    private final List<String> servers;
    public Config(List<String> servers) { this.servers = servers; }
    public List<String> getServers() { return servers; }
}
```
Identify TWO security holes and fix them.

questions.solution:
**Hole 1 — Constructor stores external reference:**
```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("server1"));
Config c = new Config(list);
list.add("malicious-server"); // c.servers is now modified!
```

**Hole 2 — Getter returns internal reference:**
```java
c.getServers().add("injected"); // modifies internal state!
```

**Fixed version:**
```java
public final class Config {
    private final List<String> servers;

    public Config(List<String> servers) {
        this.servers = List.copyOf(servers); // immutable copy (Java 10+)
        // or: new ArrayList<>(servers);
    }

    public List<String> getServers() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(servers);
        // or: return new ArrayList<>(servers);
    }
}
```

import java.math.BigDecimal;

public final class Money {
    private final BigDecimal amount;
    private final String currency;

    public Money(BigDecimal amount, String currency) {
        if (amount == null || currency == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
        this.amount = amount;
        this.currency = currency.toUpperCase();
    }

    public Money add(Money other) {
        if (!this.currency.equals(other.currency))
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Currency mismatch");
        return new Money(this.amount.add(other.amount), this.currency);
    }

    public Money multiply(int factor) {
        return new Money(this.amount.multiply(BigDecimal.valueOf(factor)), this.currency);
    }

    public BigDecimal getAmount() { return amount; }
    public String getCurrency() { return currency; }

    @Override
    public String toString() { return amount + " " + currency; }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Money a = new Money(new BigDecimal("10.00"), "USD");
        Money b = new Money(new BigDecimal("5.50"), "USD");
        System.out.println(a.add(b));      // 15.50 USD
        System.out.println(a.multiply(3)); // 30.00 USD
        System.out.println(a);             // still 10.00 USD (immutable!)
    }
}

